import java.util.Arrays;
class main{
    public static int [] rotate(int [] a){
        int n, k=4;
        int [] b= new int[a.length];
        n= a.length;
        int i;
       k=k%n;
       for(i=0; i<n; i++){
           b[(i+k)%n]=a[i];
       }
       return b;
    }
    public static void main (String [] args){
        int [] a = {1,2,3,4,5,6,7};
        int [] result= rotate(a);
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(result));
    }
}
I archieve array rotation by taking input array  followed by creating new array. asssigning my each index value to the new array here i archive rotation or shifting of
elements by using the modulo operator. (i+k)%n) for each iteration i adding my index i value with k value  and i use modulo operator with my array length
